    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p><code>package-info.java</code>: &quot;This file is new in JDK 5.0, and is preferred over package.html.&quot;—<a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/technotes/tools/unix/javadoc.html#packagecomment\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><em>javadoc - The Java API Documentation Generator</em></a></p>\n<p>Addendum: The big difference seems to be <em>package annotations</em>. There's a little more in the way of rationale in <a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se8/html/jls-7.html#jls-7.4\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><em>7.4 Package Declarations</em></a>.</p>\n<p>Addendum: The annotation feature is also mentioned <a href=\"http://tech.puredanger.com/2007/02/28/package-annotations/\" rel=\"noreferrer\">here</a> and in <a href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20080204050234/http://blogs.sun.com/darcy/entry/javadoc_tip_prefer_package_info\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><em>Javadoc tip: Prefer package-info to package.html</em></a>, cited <a href=\"https://github.com/jddarcy/BlogsSunComArchive#2006\" rel=\"noreferrer\">here</a>.</p>\n<p>Addendum: See also <a href=\"https://www.intertech.com/Blog/whats-package-info-java-for/\" rel=\"noreferrer\"><em>What’s <code>package-info.java</code> for?</em></a>.</p>\n"
  } ],
